04616nam a22005415i 9780773557550DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20192019xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735575507 a10.1515/97807735575502doi  a(DE-B1597)656479  a(OCoLC)1080218448  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBX1766 7aHIS0060202bisacsh04a282/.712231 aAnderson, Kevin P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNot Quite Us :bAnti-Catholic Thought in English Canada since 1900 /cKevin P. Anderson. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b10 tables, 6 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Religion ;v28300tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tAbbreviations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tCorrupting Democracy: French Canada, Immigration, and Anti-Catholicism in the “Progressive Era,” 1900–1929 -- tFascism and “The Revenge of the Cradle”: Anti-Catholicism and the Great Depression -- tConscription and the “Omnicompetent State”: The Second World War and Anti-Catholicism -- tWhat It Means to Be (Truly) Canadian: Cold War Anti-Catholicism and the Transformation of Britishness in Canada, 1945–1965 -- tAnti-Catholicism, 1970s–1990s: The Strange Survival of an Old Prejudice -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn twentieth-century Canada, mainline Protestants, fundamentalists, liberal nationalists, monarchists, conservative Anglophiles, and left-wing intellectuals had one thing in common: they all subscribed to a centuries-old world view that Catholicism was an authoritarian, regressive, untrustworthy, and foreign force that did not fit into a democratic, British nation like Canada. Analyzing the connections between anti-Catholicism and national identity in English Canada, Not Quite Us examines the consistency of anti-Catholic tropes in the public and private discourses of intellectuals, politicians, and clergymen, such as Arthur Lower, Eugene Forsey, Harold Innis, C.E. Silcox, F.R. Scott, George Drew, and Emily Murphy, along with those of private Canadians. Challenging the misconception that an allegedly secular, civic, and more tolerant nationalism that emerged excised its Protestant and British cast, Kevin Anderson determines that this nationalist narrative was itself steeped in an exclusionary Anglo-Protestant understanding of history and values. He shows that over time, as these ideas were dispersed through editorials, cartoons, correspondence, literature, and lectures, they influenced Canadians' intimate perceptions of themselves and their connection to Britain, the ethno-religious composition of the nation, the place of religion in public life, and national unity. Anti-Catholicism helped shape what it means to be "Canadian" in the twentieth century. Not Quite Us documents how equating Protestantism with democracy and individualism permeated ideas of national identity and continues to define Canada into the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAnti-CatholicismzCanadaxHistory. 0aCatholicszCanadaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311127268908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019z978311127498040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077355755040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773557550423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773557550/original  a978-3-11-127268-9  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3